<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Andropogon</i> <i>glomeratus</i> or <i>Schoenus</i> <i>nigricans</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Eleocharis</i> <i>rostellata</i>, <i>Epipactis</i> <i>gigantea</i>, <i>Juncus</i> <i>cooperi</i>, <i>Muhlenbergia</i> <i>utilis</i>, <i>Solidago</i> <i>confinis</i> and <i>Solidago</i> <i>spectabilis</i>. Although a shrub layer is usually lacking, scattered shrubs can occur including <i>Baccharis</i> <i>sergiloides</i>, <i>Pluchea</i> <i>sericea</i>, <i>Prosopis</i> spp. and <i>Tamarix</i> spp. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 2 m; cover is intermittent to continuous. Shrub layer is sparse to open. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Andropogon glomeratus </i>or <i>Schoenus nigricans </i>dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Calcareous seeps and springs, especially along slopes with horizontal fractures in limestone slopes or sandstone canyon walls, or other bedrock springs that flow out to the toeslopes and valley bottoms beyond. Soils are silty to clayey loams. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Andropogon glomeratus </i>as a FACW plant and <i>Schoenus nigricans </i>as a OBL plant. </div>
</div>

        
