<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Andropogon glomeratus </i>, an indicator species for this alliance, is a perennial cespitose grass with stems to 1.5 m height and is tolerant of alkalinity. It is found from the southwestern to the eastern United States in brackish, freshwater and calcareous wetland sites. In California, stands appear to be localized in alkali, carbonate springs and seeps flowing out from travertine or limestone slopes in a fine-scale mosaic with other herbs, shrubs, and trees, including rare plants such as <i>Fimbristylis thermalis</i>.<br/>
<br/>
The alliance forms lush herbaceous stands with various herbs, including the following dominants in California: <i>Andropogon glomeratus, Eleocharis rostellata, Muhlenbergia utilis, </i>and/or <i>Schoenus nigricans</i>, plus other dominants outside of California like <i>Calamagrostis scopulorum</i>. The shrub layer is typically lacking, though shrubs and trees may occur just below or around the herbaceous patches containing the springs. More sampling and analysis is needed. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
