    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>In California, this alliance is known from surveys in Death Valley NP. The hanging garden seep group was also mapped at Lake Mead NRA along the border with Grand Canyon - Parashant National Monument and other areas in the desert Southwest. There are occurrences of <i>Andropogon glomeratus </i>and <i>Schoenus nigricans </i>in the Southern California Mountains and Valleys such as the San Gabriel and San Bernardino ranges (including M262Ba, Bd-e, Bg, Bp), but we need more sampling to confirm whether stands form in alkali seeps/springs in areas outside of the Mojave Desert.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ab, Ad, Ah). The alliance was sampled and mapped at low elevations in Death Valley NP, west of the Amargosa Range in the Big Horn Springs, Ratatat Spring, Nevares Springs, and Travertine Springs complex (Evens et al. 2014). Patches are also noted from the Avawatz Mountains along limestone and granitic slopes with permanent springs (UCB 2019).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> While stands in California are found in protected areas such as Death Valley National Monument, decreasing water availability due to droughts and water extraction is a threat to stands. For example, the Nevares Springs discharge water around a travertine mound, where the National Park Service staff have placed a concrete spring box to supply water for housing. Generally, human disturbance and water extraction have altered most spring sources in this park, including the presence of excavated channels, tunnels, pipes, spring boxes, and surface flow reductions (Sada and Cooper 2012).  Restoration of springs through management planning includes monitoring long-term water level changes due to human water usage, the return of more natural spring discharge and groundwater recharge, and the removal of non-native invasive plants such as <i>Phoenix dactylifera </i>and <i>Tamarix ramosissima</i> (Sada and Cooper 2012). </div>
</div>

    

    

